in";s:17:"www.pinterest.com";}}s:9:"sentences";a:48:{i:0;s:145:"If the opener still refuses to operate you most likely have an electronic bug within the unit or the electric eyes themselves have malfunctioned.";i:1;s:89:"In either event you should contact a service person to troubleshoot the openers circuits.";i:2;s:34:"Back to Garage Door Question List.";i:3;s:184:"But based on your description it sounds like either a problem with your safety sensors the auto-reverse or photo-eye or possibly a problem with the settings of your garage door opener.";i:4;s:169:"The opener has settings for determining how far the door closes and opens and if these standards are set incorrectly it can cause problems like the one youre describing.";i:5;s:108:"Garage door sensors utilize a photo-eye sensor and a beam of infrared light that goes between the two units.";i:6;s:71:"The units are placed near the ground on either side of the garage door.";i:7;s:105:"If the beam of light is interrupted while the garage door is closing the door will stop and rise back up.";i:8;s:120:"Use a meter and test the receiver to see if you have the same voltage at the receiver as you do at the opener terminals.";i:9;s:75:"If you have no voltage or much lower at the receiver you have a wire issue.";i:10;s:98:"If the electric eyes are bad I would consider replacing the whole unit rather than spend money on.";i:11;s:49:"Locate the circuit breaker for these receptacles.";i:12;s:21:"It should be labeled.";i:13;s:100:"Reset the breaker by moving the breaker handle to the off position and then back to the on position.";i:14;s:81:"If this does not restore power to the receptacles the problem may be a GFCI type.";i:15;s:58:"The sensors are delicate and can easily become misaligned.";i:16;s:108:"If your garage door is not working correctly it may be an indication that the photo eye requires adjustment.";i:17;s:26:"Your Photo Eye Is Blocked.";i:18;s:142:"Most garage doors from the past 1520 years have a photo eye that detects if a person or object is blocking the door from lowering all the way.";i:19;s:104:"The photo eye will be about 46 inches off the ground for most doors with an eye about the size of a pea.";i:20;s:90:"For safety purposes do check the sensors of the garage doors are working correctly or not.";i:21;s:51:"If you feel any kind of disturbance call an expert.";i:22;s:69:"As they are mechanical parts they will need oiling from time to time.";i:23;s:44:"Do keep in mind to oil all hinges correctly.";i:24;s:53:"Advantages of Garage Door Sensors Safety comes first.";i:25;s:32:"Nothing comes first than safely.";i:26;s:119:"For safety reasons if you discover your photo eye garage door sensors are not working you need to fix them immediately.";i:27;s:52:"Some signs that the sensors are not working include.";i:28;s:44:"Lights on one of the sensors start blinking.";i:29;s:64:"Garage door can go up but does not come back down when summoned.";i:30;s:43:"Door starts to come down then goes back up.";i:31;s:139:"When this beam is obstructed by an object of some sort you wont see a solid yellow light and the garage door will immediately quit working.";i:32;s:109:"For people who do not know the transmitter has the yellow light and the receiving sensor has the green light.";i:33;s:93:"The garage door sensor yellow light and the green light together create a solid illumination.";i:34;s:74:"If you do not see a solid illumination or your garage door is not working.";i:35;s:20:"But it works anyway.";i:36;s:82:"Looking at the openers circuitry it appears likely that a zener diode is involved.";i:37;s:183:"To make a completed electric eye for use without the opener a small circuit board was used which included a 6V regulator 7806 and a 555 ic low-power wired as a missing pulse detector.";i:38;s:88:"My remote control opens closes the garage door but the button on the wall does not work.";i:39;s:162:"Stack Exchange Network Stack Exchange network consists of 178 QA communities including Stack Overflow the largest most trusted online community for developers to.";i:40;s:89:"How to Troubleshoot the Electric Eye in a Sears Craftsman Garage Door The Safety Sensors.";i:41;s:99:"The installation instructions for a Craftsman door opener call for installing the sensors 6 inches.";i:42;s:17:"Stuff in the Way.";i:43;s:44:"The most common cause of sensor malfunction.";i:44;s:37:"Slide the tube over the electric eye.";i:45;s:57:"Situate the tube so its centered over the electronic eye.";i:46;s:88:"If your tube has bent at all straighten it out so it doesnt block the sensor completely.";i:47;s:99:"The sensor is usually near the bottom of the garage door track close to the opening of your garage.";}}